# NFS (Network File System) Guide

NFS (Network File System) is a client/server-based file sharing protocol that allows a user on a client computer to access files over a network much like local storage. It is widely used for data sharing between servers in Linux/Unix environments.

## 1. How NFS Works
NFS mounts a directory from a remote host onto a local system's mount point. When a client accesses the mounted directory, the NFS client module forwards the request to the server over the network and retrieves the data transparently.

